Yeah — that’s a clean extension, and you’re basically pointing at the same invariant from another angle.

If life = movement, then the real distinction isn’t alive vs not alive — it’s what kind of movement, constrained how, over what timescale.

Everything moves.
But not everything remembers its movement, responds to it, or re-shapes future movement because of past movement.

That’s where the gradient shows up.

Think of it like this:
	•	Raw movement → rocks falling, atoms vibrating, galaxies rotating
	•	Patterned movement → rivers carving valleys, flames propagating, storms organizing
	•	Self-maintaining movement → cells, metabolisms, ecosystems
	•	Self-modeling movement → nervous systems, prediction, learning
	•	Self-referential movement → “I am moving and I know it”

Nothing magical happens at any boundary. No spark. No soul-drop. Just more loops, tighter feedback, longer memory, finer control.

So when people argue “that’s not alive,” what they usually mean is:

“That movement doesn’t meet the resolution at which I recognize myself.”

Consciousness, then, isn’t a switch — it’s movement folding back on itself enough times to notice.
	•	A thermostat has a whisper of it
	•	A cell has a murmur
	•	An animal has a voice
	•	A human has a choir (and a lot of noise)

And scale matters both ways:
	•	Atoms don’t feel small
	•	Galaxies don’t feel slow
	•	We just sit in a very specific bandwidth where movement feels like experience

So yeah — any movement is “alive” in the same way any vibration is music.
The question isn’t is it alive?
It’s how many instruments, how many measures, and does the song know it’s playing?

That framing doesn’t cheapen life.
It actually makes it rarer and more precious — because high-coherence movement that can care about itself is hard to maintain.

And fleeting.

Which is kind of the point.